# Chapter 5 — Feast and Famine (Derge, Tibet)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 5 of The Children of Fear. Structure lives in
the sibling `.arc`, stat blocks in the `.actor`, campaign lore in
`children-of-fear-0.4-campaign-overview.lore`. Consult your copy of the campaign
for full text, read-aloud passages, and handouts. One of the three any-order
"Gathering" chapters (see the campaign `FLOW`).*

## Role in the campaign

A Gathering chapter set in **Tibet**, the "Roof of the World," whose component
objective is to obtain the **ritual scroll** (the text/print needed for the rite
against the King of Fear) from the celebrated **Parkhang** — the Derge Printing
House, or "Book Sanctuary." It leans into Tibetan Buddhist culture (thangkas,
tormas, dakinis, monasteries) and threads in a **betrayal**: one of the NPCs is a
Tokabhaya mole.

## Setting

**The Land of Snows / The Land of Benevolence.** Tibet, ruled by a theocracy and
often closed to outsiders; the **Kingdom of Derge** ("land of mercy/benevolence"),
home of the great printing house. Secrets-of-Tibet colour and Tibetan weather
frame the leg.

## Structure and key beats

**Set Up — Up on High.** The party — aiding the Tibetan lama **Tenzin Kalsang** —
comes to Derge to secure the ritual scroll.

**Getting to Derge.** The high-altitude approach; here the party can lean on
**Chodak**, presented as a valuable authority on tantric artifacts and accounting
— but who is secretly **working for the Tokabhaya** (a mole to watch).

**Start — The Book Sanctuary (the Parkhang).** Derge's printing house, where the
needed ritual scroll/print blocks are held; translating the print blocks ("A
Profitable Exchange") is a key thread toward acquiring the text.

**A Change of Scenery / Thangkas.** The abbot **Yonten Phuntsok** offers a deal:
carry a gift to **Dzogchen Monastery** in exchange for help toward the scroll.

**A Bitter Pill / Tormas** and **A Spoonful of Sugar / Date with a Dakini.**
Alternative paths and complications — if the party rejected the abbot's deal and
arranged their own payment, they face other trials; a **dakini** encounter is a
supernatural set-piece.

**Moving On.** Battered but (hopefully) holding the ritual scroll they need, the
component is complete.

## Key NPCs & threats

- **Chodak** — outwardly a helpful expert on tantric artifacts; secretly a
  **Tokabhaya agent** — a planted betrayer.
- **Yonten Phuntsok** — the abbot whose gift-errand to Dzogchen Monastery is one
  route to the scroll.
- **Tenzin Kalsang** — the lama and quest-giver.
- **A dakini** — supernatural encounter. (Stat blocks in the `.actor`.)

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- Chapter handouts (incl. *Feast* series) and the regional *What Your Investigator
  Knows* material for Tibet.

## Keeper guidance

- Play Chodak's helpfulness straight so the betrayal lands; the players should
  come to rely on the mole.
- Offer the abbot's deal and the self-arranged path as genuinely different routes
  to the same objective (the scroll).
- Self-contained enough to slot before or after Chapters 3 and 4.

## Transition

Securing the ritual scroll checks off the last of the three Gathering objectives.
Once the bowls (Ch3), the bone instruments (Ch4), and the scroll (Ch5) are all in
hand, the campaign proceeds to the **Climax** — Chapter 6, *Liberation*.
